<P>
<B>Economic and Political Theory: Federalism</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
<ul>
<b>Books:</b>
<p>
<a href="/heritage/issues96/chpt14.html">Federalism</a> by Douglas Seay and Wesley R. Smith.  (<i>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</i>)<p>
<b>Policy Papers:</b>
<p>
<li>10/28/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg1097.html">How State and Local Officials Can Combat Violent Juvenile Crime</a>  by James Wootton and Robert O. Heck. (State Backgrounder #1097/S)
<li>9/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/sept96/cal.html">Out of Order</a> By Steven G. Calabresi. (September-October 1996, Policy Review: The Journal of American
 Citizenship)
<li>9/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/sept96/labs.html">Don't Brake for Big Government</a> by Tyce Palmaffy. (September-October 1996, Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)
<li>9/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/sept96/truths.html">Who Owns the Sidewalks?</a> by Stephen Goldsmith. (September-October 1996, Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)
<li>8/6/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg1089.html">Getting Backup: Twenty-One Steps Public Officials Can Take To Support Their Local Police</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert E. Moffit</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/meese.htm">Edwin Meese III</a>. (State Backgrounder No. 1089)
<li>5/1/96 <a href="/heritage/resource_bank/inmay6fea.html">The States and The People: An Historic Coalition</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/atwood.htm">Thomas C. Atwood</a>. (May 1996 <i>Insider</i>) 

<li>5/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/may96/norqu.html">Spirit of '96</a> by Grover Norquist.  (May-June 1996 Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)


<li>4/25/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/theory/lect567.html">Liberating People for Self-Government</a> by Mayor Stephen Goldsmith. (Heritage Lecture #567)


<li>4/8/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/education/bg1076.html">How Congress Can Restore Local and Parental Control Over Education</a> by Denis Philip Doyle and Christine Olson. (Backgrounder #1076)

<li>3/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/mar96/abuses.html">Big Government Junkies</a> by John P. Walters.  (March-April Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)

<li>1/5/96 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/family/lect554.html">Less From Washington, More from Us: A Citizenship Agenda for a Rising, Shining America</a> by Lamar Alexander.  (Lecture #554)

<li>1/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/coats.html">Can Congress Restore Civil Society?</a> by Dan Coats.  (January-February 1996 Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)

<li>1/1/96 <a href="/heritage/p_review/jan96/abuses.html">Bus-jacking the Revolution</a> by John Walters. (January-February 1996 Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship)

<li>7/27/95 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/lect535.html">Federalism on the Hudson: The Empire State Strikes Back</a> by the Hon. George Pataki, Governor of New York. (Heritage Lecture #535)

<li>7/1/95 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/prabra.html">Litigation Tariff: The Federalist Case for National Tort Reform</a> by Spencer Abraham (Summer 1995 Policy Review)

<li>6/29/95 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/enviro/lect534.html">A Federalist's Approach To Protecting the Environment</a> by The Hon. Fife Symington, Governor of Arizona. (Heritage Lecture #534)

<li>12/28/94 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1011.html">Home Rule: How States are Fighting Unfunded Federal Mandates</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/atwood.htm">Thomas Atwood</a> and Chris West. (State Backgrounder #1011)

<li>10/11/94 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/fyi40.html">Reining in Federal Judges: The Crime Bill's Unexpected Gift to the States</a> by Wesley Smith and Douglas Seay. (F.Y.I. No. 40)


<li>8/16/94 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/fyi29.html">The Crime Bill's Faulty Math Means a $28 Billion Unfunded Liability to the States</a> by <a href="/heritage/staff/hodge.htm">Scott A. Hodge</a>. (F.Y.I. No. 29)

<li>6/7/93 <a href="/heritage/library/categories/crimelaw/bg944.html"> How States Can Fight Violent Crime: Two Dozen Steps to a Safer America</a> by Mary Kate Cary (Backgrounder #944/S)

</ul><p>
