<html>
<head>
<title>The Unveiling of the Innovation Age</title>  
</head>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> 
<blockquote><ul>
<a href="/pff/"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>

<center>
<h2>The Unveiling of the Innovation Age </h2>
</center>

On behalf of Hudson Institute and The Progress & Freedom Foundation, I am pleased to invite you to a special briefing on Wednesday, September 11 to unveil Hudson's latest book,<i> The Innovation Age:  A New Perspective on the Telecom Revolution</i>.  The book's author is Hudson and PFF adjunct fellow Peter Pitsch, former Chief of Staff and Chief of Planning at the Federal Communications Commission.<p>


Mr. Pitsch will provide opening remarks, and we have asked <b>Congressman Bob Walker</b> (R-PA) to do the same.  Serving as panel discussants will be <b>William E. Cohen</b>, Deputy Director, Policy Planning, for the Federal Trade Commission and <b> Blair Levin</b>, Chief of Staff for Chairman Reed Hundt of the Federal Communications Commission.  In discussing Mr. Pitsch's new book, they will attempt to answer the following questions:<p>
<ul> 
<li>Is the "Innovation Age" real?
<li>Does it require developing a new political economy of innovation?
<li>Has it strengthened the comparative advantage of marketplace solutions vis--vis regulation?
<li>Are the book's proposed reforms to telecommunications regulation desirable?
</ul>
	Advancements in computer and digital information technologies have created an era of rapid economic and technological change which Mr. Pitsch calls the "Innovation Age."  In the book, he describes how the resulting complexity and potential for explosive growth have increased the cost of regulatory distortions, especially in the telecommunications market.  Peter Passell of <i>The New York Times</i> calls <i>The Innovation Age </I>  "painless introduction to the way economists are now rethinking regulation."<p>

	<i>This special briefing will be held from 1:30 to 3:30 p.m. on Wednesday, September 11, in Room 106 of Dirksen Senate Office Building.</i>  If you would like additional information, please call Mary Brown, Hudson's Director of Special Events, at 317-549-4150.  We hope you will be able to stop by.<p>


<p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" 
border="0" ISMAP></a></center>

</blockquote></ul>
<P>
