<HTML>
<HEAD><META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z"><TITLE>Center for Political Renewal -- PFF</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="backgrnd.gif" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<map name="wst">
<area shape="rect" coords="0,0,92,20" href="#works">
<area shape="rect" coords="93,0,193,20" href="#speeches">
<area shape="rect" coords="194,0,318,20" href="#testimonies"></map>

<ul><blockquote>

<a href="welcome.html"><img src="bi.gif" align="right" border="0" alt="PFF"></a>
<center>
<a href="wst.map"><img src="wst.gif" border="0" USEMAP="#wst" ISMAP></a>
<img src="cprhead.gif" alt="Center for Political Renewal">
</center>
<br><br><P>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign="top" width="20%">The talk in Washington is all about the end of the old party system.
 Not FDR's grand coalition (already dead!), but the two parties
themselves, the party system itself, seems to be unraveling. 
Are rebel voters, renegade factions, and brash new parties just
perturbations on an historical continuum? Or is the Old Order
really tottering?  And if it goes, what rises to take its place?
<P>
From where does all this voter anger arise?  Why do they feel
so alienated from their government?  The current structure of
the Federal government - centralized, bureaucratic decision making
in Washington to solve the nation's problems - came to the fore
in the 1930s and has reigned supreme ever since.  Until today.
 What type of governmental structures are needed for the 21st
century?  Is it time to replace the industrial state?
<P>
<td valign="top">
<ul><a name="works"></a>
<img src="bullet.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><big>Works</big>
<P><ul>
<img src="diamond.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><a href="/pff/cpr/higg0216.html"><b>How to Speak up for the GOP Revolution</a></b> by Heather Higgins<br>
<img src="diamond.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><a href="/pff/cpr/huff0214.html"><b>A Seven Step Recovery Program</a></b> by Arianna Huffington<br>
<img src="diamond.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><a href="/pff/odon0209.html"><b>Republican Dreaming</b></a> by Rick O'Donnell<br>
<img src="diamond.gif"  align="top" hspace="5"><a href="webe0125.html"><b>Reflections on the Revolution</b></a> by Vin Weber  
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top"><b><a href="mv011896.html">Are We Reliving the 1850s?</a></b> by Michael Vlahos
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top"><a href="odon0125.html"><b>Whose Values Mr. President?</b></a> by Rick O'Donnell 
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top"><a href="ncp_beyond-block-grants.html"><b>Beyond Block Grants</b></a> by Timothy J. Muris 
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="pr_civiil-society-role-renew.html"><b>Civil Society, Social Disorder, and the Role of Politics in Renewal</a></b> by Don Eberly
<P>
</ul>
<a name="speeches"></a>
<img src="bullet.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><big>Speeches</big>
<ul>
<img src="diamond.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><a href="/pff/cpr/nmajo321.html"><b>In Search of the New Majority</b></a>: Remarks by Vin Weber, Frank Luntz and Andrew Kohut at PFF's New Majority Conference.<P>

<img src="diamond.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><a href="/pff/cpr/tnmlunch.html"><b>The State of the Revolution:</a></b>  remarks by Newt Gingrich, Preston Manning Iwao Matsuda, and John Redwood at PFF's New Majority Conference.
<P>
<img src="diamond.gif" align="top" hspace="5"><a href="/pff/cpr/majconf.html"><b>The Future of the Revolution:</a></b>  remarks by Jim Miller, Arianna Huffington, Grover Norquist, Chuck Kelly, Bill Galston, Michael Barone and Heather Higgins at PFF's New Majority Conference.<br>
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top"><a href="amciv/ac-july/ac795fs.html"><b>Who Lost Japan?</a></b> interview with Alvin Toffler 
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top"><a href="speeches/sp895je.html"><B>Discussion on Conservatism</b></a> by Jeff Eisenach
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" vspace="4" align="top"><a href="Lessons4.html"><b>The Lessons of the 1992 and 1994 Elections</a></b> by Vin Weber
<br><img src="diamond.gif" hspace="5" align="top"><a href="pff16.html"><b>Reasserting States Rights</a></b> interview with Governor Mike Leavitt<br>
<P>
</ul>
<P><a name="testimonies"></a>
